{"title_page": "Jeremy Howard (entrepreneur)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Jeremy Howard\n| image                     = Jeremy Howard.jpg\n| image_size                = 180px\n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Howard in [[Maui]], 2014\n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1973|11|13}}\n| birth_place               = [[London, England]]\n| residence                 = [[San Francisco, California]]\n| nationality               = Australian\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = \n| other_names               = \n| known_for                 = Work in [[Deep Learning]], [[Machine Learning]]\n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| employer                  = \n| notable works             =\n| occupation                = Founding Researcher at [http://www.fast.ai/ fast.ai], Chief Executive Officer and Founder of [http://www.enlitic.com Enlitic], Distinguished Research Scientist at the [[University of San Francisco]], Data Science Faculty Member at [http://singularityu.org/bio/jeremy-howard/ Singularity University], Young Global Leader at the [[World Economic Forum]]\n| years_active              = \n| spouse                    = \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = \n| parents                   = \n| relations                 = \n| awards                    =  Winner of global [[Kaggle]] Data Science Competitions, 2011 and 2010<ref name=\"kaggle.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kaggle.com/c/tourism1/Leaderboard|title=Kaggle leaderboard for Tourism Forecasting Part One}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kaggle.com/c/unimelb/Leaderboard|title=Kaggle leaderboard for Predicting Grant Applications}}</ref> \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| website                   = http://jhoward.fastmail.fm.user.fm/\n}}\n\n'''Jeremy Howard''' (born 13 November 1973) is an Australian data scientist and entrepreneur.<ref name=\"itwire\">{{cite news|title=Opera acquires Aussie IMAP email provider FastMail.fm|url=http://www.itwire.com/it-industry-news/deals/38696-opera-acquires-aussie-imap-email-provider-fastmailfm}}</ref> He is a founding researcher at [http://www.fast.ai/ fast.ai], a research institute dedicated to make [[Deep learning|Deep Learning]] more accessible. Previously, he was the CEO and Founder at [http://www.enlitic.com Enlitic], an advanced machine learning company in [[San Francisco, California]]. Prior to it, Howard was the President and Chief Scientist at [[Kaggle]], a community and competition platform of over 200,000 data scientists. Howard is the youngest faculty member at [[Singularity University]], where he teaches data science.  He is also a [[Young Global Leader]] with the [[World Economic Forum]], and spoke at the World Economic Forum Annual Meeting 2014 on \"Jobs For The Machines.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74xPTVQx0Lc\n|title=Jobs for The Machines}}</ref> Howard advised [[Khosla Ventures]] as their Data Strategist, identifying the biggest opportunities for investing in data-driven startups and mentoring their portfolio companies to build data-driven businesses. Howard was the founding CEO of two successful Australian startups, [[FastMail]] and [http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2008/02/05/87032.htm Optimal Decisions Group]. Before that, he spent eight years in management consulting, at [[McKinsey & Company]] and [[AT Kearney]].\n\n== Early life and background ==\nHoward was born in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]], and moved to [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] in 1976. He attended [[Melbourne Grammar]] and studied philosophy at the [[University of Melbourne]].\n\n== Career ==\nHoward started his career in management consulting, working at some of the world's most exclusive firms.  Described as a \"wunderkind\",<ref name=\"itwire\" /> he was earning over $200,000 while still a 19-year-old student in the Australian offices of [[McKinsey & Company]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Later, he became the youngest Engagement Manager world-wide at [[AT Kearney]], creating a new global practice in what is now referred to as [[Big Data]].  He remained in management consulting for eight years before becoming an entrepreneur.\n\nEarly in his career, Howard contributed to open source projects, particularly the [[Perl]] programming language, [[Cyrus IMAP server]], and [[Postfix (software)|Postfix]] SMTP server. He helped develop the Perl language, as chair of the [[Raku (programming language)|Perl6-data]] working group, and author of RFCs.\n\nWhile in Australia, Howard founded two successful startups: the email provider [[FastMail.FM]], which he sold to [[Opera Software]], and the insurance pricing optimization company [http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/national/2008/02/05/87032.htm Optimal Decisions Group] (ODG),  which he sold to [[ChoicePoint]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McCaul|first=Fiona|title=ChoicePoint acquires Optimal Decisions Group (ODG) to Enhance Insurance Analytics Capabilities|url=http://news.thomasnet.com/companystory/ChoicePoint-Acquires-Optimal-Decision-Group-ODG-to-Enhance-Insurance-Analytics-Capabilities-812507|newspaper=ThomasNet|date=5 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[FastMail]] was one of the first email products that enabled users to integrate their familiar desktop clients.   In a comparison of the world's top web-based email systems, [[PC World]] ranked FastMail.FM and [[GMail]] as the superior services, saying  \"if you take your e-mail seriously, FastMail is the service for you.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=FastMail - professional email services|url=http://www.pastlifeastrology.com/Samples/Angel_files/image004.htm}}</ref>\n\nHoward founded Optimal Decisions Group on the basis that a company's most important strategic decision is often how to optimize actionable outcomes with predictive models.  ODG addressed this need with one of the early uses of the widely applicable Drivetrain Approach,<ref>{{cite news|title=Designing great data products - The Drivetrain Approach: A four-step process for building data products|url=http://radar.oreilly.com/2012/03/drivetrain-approach-data-products.html | date=28 March 2012 | publisher=O'Reilly | first1=Jeremy | last1=Howard | first2=Margit | last2=Zwemer | first3=Mike | last3=Loukides | accessdate=4 October 2018 }}</ref> and applied the Approach to develop insurance pricing algorithms.  As of Q4 2014, both Optimal Decisions Group and FastMail  are still operational.\n\n=== Kaggle ===\nHoward first became involved with [[Kaggle]], founded in April 2010,<ref>{{cite news|last=Rao|first=Leena|title=Index And Khosla Lead $11M Round In Kaggle, A Platform For Data Modeling Competitions|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/11/02/index-and-khosla-lead-11m-round-in-kaggle-a-platform-for-data-modeling-competitions/|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=TechCrunch|date=2 November 2011}}</ref> after becoming the globally top-ranked participant in data science competitions in both 2010 and 2011.  The competitions that Howard won involved tourism forecasting<ref name=\"kaggle.com\"/> and predicting the success of grant applications.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  Howard then became the President and Chief Scientist of Kaggle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaggle.com/pages/team|title=Kaggle - Our Team}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, [[Wired Magazine]] ran a piece on Howard, calling him 'The Accidental Scientist' and relaying his observations on the tendency of Silicon Valley to be \"something of an echo chamber.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Metz|first=Cade|title=Accidental Scientist Hawks 'Online Marketplace for Brains'|url=https://www.wired.com/wiredenterprise/2011/12/kaggle/|newspaper=Wired|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>  Howard was also interviewed by the [[McKinsey Quarterly]], where he explained that the rapid advance of machine learning presents an economic paradox; while productivity is rising, employment may not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mckinsey.com/insights/public_sector/the_great_decoupling|title=McKinsey Quarterly - The Great Decoupling}}</ref>  By December 2013, Howard had left his position as President of Kaggle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quora.com/Kaggle/Why-did-Jeremy-Howard-leave-Kaggle-What-are-his-plans-now|title=Quora - Why did Jeremy Howard leave Kaggle? What are his plans now?}}</ref>\n\n=== Enlitic ===\nIn August 2014, Howard founded Enlitic with the mission of leveraging recent advances in [[machine learning]] to make medical diagnostics and clinical decision support tools faster, more accurate, and more accessible. \nEnlitic uses state-of-the-art [[Deep Learning]] algorithms to diagnose illness and disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mckinsey.com/insights/strategy/artificial_intelligence_meets_the_c-suite|title=McKinsey Quarterly - Artificial intelligence meets the C-suite}}</ref>  Howard believes that today, machine learning algorithms are actually as good as or better than humans at many things that we think of as being uniquely human capabilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/08/enlitic/|title=The Data Scientist on a Quest to Turn Computers Into Doctors|date=22 August 2014|first=Klint|last=Finley|work=Wired|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> He projects that the application of deep learning will have the most significant impact on medicine out of any technology during this decade by effectively aggregating data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/news/530261/a-startup-hopes-to-teach-computers-to-spot-tumors-in-medical-scans/|title=A Startup Hopes to Teach Computers to Spot Tumors in Medical Scans}}</ref> \nOn 28 October 2014, Howard announced Enlitic's seed funding round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/10/28/enlitic-funding/|title=Enlitic picks up $2M to help diagnose diseases with deep learning}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and interests==\nHoward used [[Spaced repetition|Spaced Repetitive Learning]] to develop usable Chinese language skills in just one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quantifiedself.com/2012/05/jeremy-howard-on-language-acquisition-performance/|title=Jeremy Howard on Language Acquisition Performance}}</ref> Jeremy has mentored and advised many startups, and is also an angel investor. He has contributed to a range of open-source projects as a developer, and was a regular guest expert on Australia's most popular TV morning news program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]''.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://jhoward.fastmail.fm/}}\n* [http://singularityu.org/bio/jeremy-howard/ Personal bio at Singularity University]\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/jeremy_howard_the_wonderful_and_terrifying_implications_of_computers_that_can_learn#t-813093 Jeremy Howard: The wonderful and terrifying implications of computers that can learn] at [[TED (conference)|TED]]\n* [http://www.enlitic.com Howard's machine-learning startup, Enlitic]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard, Jeremy}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian company founders]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Jeremy Howard\n| image                     = Jeremy Howard.jpg\n| image_size                = 180px\n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Howard in [[Maui]], 2014\n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1973|11|13}}\n| birth_place               = [[London, England]]\n| residence                 = [[San Francisco, California]]\n| nationality 