nded Enlitic with the mission of leveraging recent advances in [[machine learning]] to make medical diagnostics and clinical decision support tools faster, more accurate, and more accessible. \nEnlitic uses state-of-the-art [[Deep Learning]] algorithms to diagnose illness and disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mckinsey.com/insights/strategy/artificial_intelligence_meets_the_c-suite|title=McKinsey Quarterly - Artificial intelligence meets the C-suite}}</ref>  Howard believes that today, machine learning algorithms are actually as good as or better than humans at many things that we think of as being uniquely human capabilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/08/enlitic/|title=The Data Scientist on a Quest to Turn Computers Into Doctors|date=22 August 2014|first=Klint|last=Finley|work=Wired|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> He projects that the application of deep learning will have the most significant impact on medicine out of any technology during this decade by effectively aggregating data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/news/530261/a-startup-hopes-to-teach-computers-to-spot-tumors-in-medical-scans/|title=A Startup Hopes to Teach Computers to Spot Tumors in Medical Scans}}</ref> \nOn 28 October 2014, Howard announced Enlitic's seed funding round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/10/28/enlitic-funding/|title=Enlitic picks up $2M to help diagnose diseases with deep learning}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and interests==\nHoward used [[Spaced repetition|Spaced Repetitive Learning]] to develop usable Chinese language skills in just one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quantifiedself.com/2012/05/jeremy-howard-on-language-acquisition-performance/|title=Jeremy Howard on Language Acquisition Performance}}</ref> Jeremy has mentored and advised many startups, and is also an angel investor. He has contributed to a range of open-source projects as a developer, and was a regular guest expert on Australia's most popular TV morning news program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]''.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://jhoward.fastmail.fm/}}\n* [http://singularityu.org/bio/jeremy-howard/ Personal bio at Singularity University]\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/jeremy_howard_the_wonderful_and_terrifying_implications_of_computers_that_can_learn#t-813093 Jeremy Howard: The wonderful and terrifying implications of computers that can learn] at [[TED (conference)|TED]]\n* [http://www.enlitic.com Howard's machine-learning startup, Enlitic]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard, Jeremy}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian company founders]]\n", "name_user": "Sam Watkins", "label": "safe", "comment": "correction: perl6-date -> perl6-data", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremy_Howard_(entrepreneur)"}
